{"id":"0908.2597","submitter":"Barbara Baumeister","authors":"Barbara Baumeister, Alexander Stein","title":"The finite Bruck Loops","comments":"15 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We continue the work by Aschbacher, Kinyon and Phillips [AKP] as well as of\nGlauberman [Glaub1,2] by describing the structure of the finite Bruck loops. We\nshow essentially that a finite Bruck loop $X$ is the direct product of a Bruck\nloop of odd order with either a soluble Bruck loop of 2-power order or a\nproduct of loops related to the groups $PSL_2(q)$, $q= 9$ or $q \\geq 5$ a\nFermat prime. The latter possibillity does occur as is shown in [Nag1, BS]. As\ncorollaries we obtain versions of Sylow's, Lagrange's and Hall's Theorems for\nloops.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 18 Aug 2009 15:52:18 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 14 Jul 2010 20:03:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-07-16"}
